"Crouch E.M., Heilmann-Clausen C., Brinkhuis H., Morgans H.E.G, Rogers K.M., Egger H., Schmitz B.","Global dinoflagellate event associated with the late Paleocene thermal maximum",2001,"Geology","29","4",,"315","318",,,10.1130/0091-7613(2001)029<0315:GDEAWT>2.0.CO;2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84879884152&partnerID=40&md5=bbca3f6ae01e3222621605cf85ece545","Lab. Palaeobotany/Palynology, Utrecht University, Budapestlaan 4, Utrecht, CD 3584, Netherlands; Geologisk Institut, Aarhus Universitet, DK-8000, Aarhus C, Denmark; Institute of Geological and Nuclear Sciences, P.O. Box 30-368, Lower Hutt, New Zealand; Geologische Bundesanstalt, Rasumofskygasse 23, A-1031 Vienna, Austria; Marine Geology, Earth Sciences Centre, Box 460, SE-405 30 Gôteborg, Sweden","Crouch, E.M., Lab. Palaeobotany/Palynology, Utrecht University, Budapestlaan 4, Utrecht, CD 3584, Netherlands; Heilmann-Clausen, C., Geologisk Institut, Aarhus Universitet, DK-8000, Aarhus C, Denmark; Brinkhuis, H., Lab. Palaeobotany/Palynology, Utrecht University, Budapestlaan 4, Utrecht, CD 3584, Netherlands; Morgans, H.E.G, Institute of Geological and Nuclear Sciences, P.O. Box 30-368, Lower Hutt, New Zealand; Rogers, K.M., Institute of Geological and Nuclear Sciences, P.O. Box 30-368, Lower Hutt, New Zealand; Egger, H., Geologische Bundesanstalt, Rasumofskygasse 23, A-1031 Vienna, Austria; Schmitz, B., Marine Geology, Earth Sciences Centre, Box 460, SE-405 30 Gôteborg, Sweden","The late Paleocene thermal maximum, or LPTM (ca. 55 Ma), represents a geologically brief time interval (∼220 k.y.) characterized by profound global warming and associated environmental change. The LPTM is marked by a prominent negative carbon isotope excursion (CIE) interpreted to reflect a massive and abrupt input of 12C-enriched carbon to the ocean-atmosphere reservoir, possibly as a result of catastrophic gas-hydrate release, on time scales equivalent to present-day rates of anthropogenic carbon input. The LPTM corresponds to important changes in the global distribution of biota, including mass extinction of marine benthic organisms. The dinoflagellate cyst record indicates that surface-dwelling marine plankton in marginal seas also underwent significant perturbations during the LPTM. We report on the dramatic response of representatives of the genus Apectodinium from two upper Paleocene-lower Eocene sections in the Southern (New Zealand) and Northern (Austria) Hemispheres, where the dinoflagellate records are directly correlated with the CIE, benthic foraminifera extinction event, and calcareous nannofossil zonation. The results indicate that the inception of Apectodinium-dominated assemblages appears to be synchronous on a global scale, and that the event is precisely coincident with the beginning of the LPTM. Apectodinium markedly declined in abundance near the end of the LPTM. This Apectodinium event may be associated with (1) exceptionally high global sea-surface temperatures and/or (2) a significant increase in marginal-marine surface-water productivity. Such a globally synchronous acme of dinoflagellate cysts is unprecedented within the dinoflagellate cyst fossil record.","Dinoflagellates; Late Paleocene thermal maximum","Nannofossil zonation; Carbon; Gas hydrates; Global warming; Isotopes; Perturbation techniques; Geology; dinoflagellate; global warming; mass extinction; Paleocene; paleoclimate; paleoproductivity; sea surface temperature",,,,,,"Aubry, M.-P., 1998 Early Paleogene calcareous nannoplankton evolution: A tale of climatic amelioration Late Paleocene-early Eocene Biotic and Climatic Events in the Marine and Terrestrial Records, pp. 158-203. , Aubry, M.-P., et al., eds., New York, Columbia University Press; Bains, S., Norris, R.D., Corfield, R.M., Faul, K.L., Termination of global warmth at the Paleocene/Eocene boundary through productivity feedbacks (2000) Nature, 407, pp. 171-174; Brinkhuis, H., Romein, A.J.T., Smit, J., Zachariasse, J.-W., Danian-Selandian dinoflagellate cysts from lower latitudes with special reference to the El Kef section, NW Tunisia (1994) GFF, 116, pp. 46-48; Bujak, J.P., Brinkhuis, H., Global warming and dinocyst changes across the Paleocene/Eocene Epoch boundary (1998) Late Paleocene-Early Eocene Biotic and Climatic Events in the Marine and Terrestrial Records, pp. 277-295. , Aubry, M.-P., et al., eds., New York, Columbia University Press; Clyde, W.C., Gingerich, P.D., Mammalian community response to the latest Paleocene thermal maximum: An isotaphonomic study in the northern Bighorn basin. Wyoming (1998) Geology, 26, pp. 1011-1014; Costa, L.I., Downie, C., The distribution of the dinoflagellate Wetzeliella in the Paleogene of north-western Europe (1976) Palaeontology, 19, pp. 591-614; Dickens, G.R., Carbon cycle: The blast in the past (1999) Nature, 401, pp. 752-755; Dickens, G.R., Methane oxidation during the late Paleocene thermal maximum (2000) Société Géologique de France Bulletin, 171, pp. 37-49; Dickens, G.R., O'Neil, J.R., Rea, D.K., Owen, R.M., Dissociation of oceanic methane hydrate as a cause of the carbon isotope excursion at the end of the Paleocene (1995) Paleoceanography, 10, pp. 965-971; Egger, H., Heilmann-Clausen, C., Schmitz, B., The Paleocene/Eocene boundary interval of a Tethyan deep-sea section and its correlation with the North Sea basin (2000) Société Géologique de France Bulletin, 171, pp. 207-216; Egger, H., Homayoun, M., Roegl, F., Deep-sea sedimentation and paleoproductivity in the Paleogene of a Tethyan basin (2000) GFF, 122, pp. 44-45; Fensome, R.A., Riding, J.B., Taylor, F.J.R., Dinoflagellates (1996) Palynology: Principles and Applications: American Association of Stratigraphic Palynologists Foundation, pp. 107-169. , Jansonius, J., and McGregor, D.C., eds; Heilmann-Clausen, C., Dinoflagellate stratigraphy of the uppermost Danian to Ypresian in the Viborg 1 borehole, central Jylland. Denmark (1985) Danmarks Geologiske Undersogelse, 7, pp. 1-69. , ser. A; Jan du Ch